What I learned going through High School and into 6 years of college is that people never change. Personalities and emotions change every half-second but people stay the same. In Mr. Faulk's Statics class I was all ready determined to do well. This was a precursor to a harder more practical subject that was to come in structural analysis. We were given straightforward work that had answers right there. But two boys will stand out from the class. Jordan Reynolds and Nathan Condon were jokes. Because they did none of the homework, always goofing around and when it came to tests? They rocked the house. So expect a lot of confusion when I leave high school and found that people are so much the same as they were during those long years.

Pure alcohol doesn't go bad as long as it's sealed, but over time it starts breaking down into other compounds as the alcohol begins to evaporate. That said, spirits with more flavor compounds like whiskey will maintain their flavors for a long-ass time (like, decades) if they're sealed and stored at a constant temperature. But if you taste a change in flavor, then it's probably not worth it.
